<section xml:id="sec_fourth-spfunc" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Special Functions</title>
  <introduction>
  <p>
    Special functions are specific mathematical functions that arise in the solution of 
    certain types of differential equations. These functions are often defined as solutions 
    to differential equations themselves and have unique properties that make them useful 
    in various branches of mathematics and physics. Some examples of special functions 
    commonly encountered in differential equations include: 
    <term>Legendre functions:</term> Legendre functions are solutions to Legendre's 
    differential equation, which commonly arises in problems involving the physics of 
    spherical symmetry, such as electrostatics or quantum mechanics. 
    <term>Bessel functions:</term> Bessel functions arise when solving differential 
    equations that exhibit cylindrical symmetry, such as in problems involving heat 
    conduction in cylindrical coordinates or wave propagation in circular structures. 
    <term>Hermite functions:</term> Hermite functions appear as solutions to Hermite's 
    differential equation, which frequently arises in quantum mechanics, specifically 
    in problems related to harmonic oscillators. 
    <term>Hypergeometric functions:</term> Hypergeometric functions are solutions to the 
    hypergeometric differential equation, which is a second-order linear differential equation. 
    These functions have applications in various fields, including probability theory, 
    mathematical physics, and number theory. 
    <term>Gamma and Beta functions:</term> The gamma and beta functions are defined as 
    integrals and play a significant role in solving differential equations involving 
    exponential or power functions. 
    <term>Airy functions: </term> Airy functions are solutions to Airy's differential equation, 
    which frequently arises in the study of wave phenomena, such as diffraction and interference. 
    </p>
    <p>
      <term>Laguerre functions:</term> are a family of special functions that arise in the 
      solution of certain types of differential equations, specifically the Laguerre's 
      differential equation. The Laguerre functions, denoted as <m> L_n(x)</m>, 
      are defined as solutions to the following differential equation: 
      <me>
        x*y'' + (1 - x)y' + ny = 0
      </me>
      where y'' represents the second derivative of y with respect to x, y' represents the 
      first derivative of y with respect to x, and n is a parameter that determines the solution. 
      Laguerre functions have several important properties and applications in various areas of 
      mathematics and physics. Some key properties of Laguerre functions include: 
      Orthogonality: Laguerre functions are orthogonal over the interval <m>[0, \infty)</m> 
      with respect to the weight function <m>e^{-x}</m>. Generating function: The Laguerre 
      functions can be generated by the exponential generating function: 
      <me>
        e^{-xt/(1-t)} = \sum (L_n(x)*t^n/n!, \quad n=0 \quad \text{to}\quad \infty)
      </me>
      This generating function allows for convenient manipulations and calculations involving 
      Laguerre functions. Applications: Laguerre functions find applications in various fields, 
      including quantum mechanics, mathematical physics, and probability theory. 
      They are particularly useful in solving problems related to quantum harmonic 
      oscillators, quantum field theory, and the study of atomic and molecular systems. 
      Laguerre functions are just one example of the many special functions that mathematicians 
      and scientists have developed to solve specific types of differential equations and 
      describe various physical phenomena.
      </p>
    <p>
      These special functions have distinct properties and often possess symmetry, orthogonality, 
    and recurrence relations, which make them valuable tools for solving differential equations 
    in specific contexts. They are widely used in various scientific and engineering disciplines 
    to describe physical phenomena and analyze mathematical models.
      </p>
     </introduction>
     
 <subsection xml:id="subsec-Legnd_eq">
  <title>Legendre's Differential Equation</title>
  <introduction>
   
  <p>
    The differential equation 
    <men xml:id="eqn-leg_eq1">
      (1-x^{2})\frac{\,d^{2}y}{\,dx^{2}}-2x\frac{\,dy}{\,dx}+n(n+1)y=0
    </men>
    is known as Legendre's differential equation. Such type of equation appears 
    on solving Laplace's equation (<m>\nabla^{2}y=0</m>) associated with spherical harmonics. 
    In equation <xref ref="eqn-leg_eq1"/>, <m>n</m> is any number (integer or fraction). 
    This equation can be solved in series of ascending or descending power of <m>x</m>. 
    It has no singularity at <m>x=0</m> so its solution can be obtained as a power series 
    developed about this point. 
    </p>
    <p>
      Let the series solution in descending powers of <m>x</m> be 
      <men xml:id="eqn-leg_eq2">
        y=\sum\limits_{k=0}^{\infty} a_{k}x^{m-k}
      </men>
      so that 
        <me>
          \frac{\,dy}{\,dx}=\sum a_{k}(m-k)x^{m-k-1}
        </me>
        and 
        <me>
          \frac{\,d^{2}y}{\,dx^{2}}=\sum a_{k}(m-k)(m-k-1)x^{m-k-2}
        </me>
        Substituting these in equation <xref ref="eqn-leg_eq1"/>, we get-
        <me>
          (1-x^{2})\sum a_{k}(m-k)(m-k-1)x^{m-k-2}-2x\sum a_{k}(m-k)x^{m-k-1} 
        </me>
        <me>
          +n(n+1)\sum a_{k}x^{m-k} =0
        </me>
        
        or,
        <me>
          \sum a_{k}(m-k)(m-k-1)x^{m-k-2}
        </me>
        <me>
          -\sum \{n(n+1)-(m-k)(m-k-1) -2(m-k)\}a_{k}x^{m-k}=0
        </me>
        
        or,
        <me>
           \sum a_{k}(m-k)(m-k-1)x^{m-k-2}
        </me>
        <men xml:id="eqn-leg_eq3">
         -\sum \{n(n+1) -(m-k)(m-k+1)\}a_{k}x^{m-k}=0
        </men>
        It is an identity and therefore, the coefficients of various poweers of <m>x</m> 
        must vanish. Now equating to zero, the coefficient of <m>x^{m}</m>, the highest powers 
        of <m>x</m>, we have 
        <me>
          a_{o}\{n(n+1)-m(m+1)\}=0 
        </me>
        for <m>(k=0)</m>. Since the coefficient of first term of the series can not be zero. Therefore 
        <m>a_{o} \neq 0 </m>. Hence the indicial equation is 
        <me>
           n(n+1)-m(m+1) =0
        </me>
        or,
        <me>
          n^{2} +n-m^{2}-m=0 
        </me>
        or,
        <me>
          n^{2}-m^{2}+(n-m)=0
        </me>
        or,
        <me>
          (n-m)(n+m+1) =0
        </me>
        or,
       <men xml:id="eqn-leg_eq4">
          m=n \quad \text{and}\quad m=-n-1. 
       </men>
       
        Next equating the coefficient of <m>x^{m-1}</m> to zero, we get -
        <me>
          a_{1}\left[n(n+1)-(m-1)m\right] =0
        </me>
        or,
        <me>
          a_{1}\left[n^{2}+n-m^{2}+m\right] =0
        </me>
        or,
        <me>
          a_{1}\left[(n+m)+(n+m)(n-m)\right] =0
        </me>
        or,
        <me>
          a_{1}(n+m)\{n-m+1\} =0
        </me>
        but,
        <me>
          (n+m)(n-m+1) \neq 0, 
        </me>
        for <m>m=n,-n-1</m>.
        Hence,
        <men xml:id="eqn-leg_eq5">
          a_{1}=0
        </men>
        Again, equating the coefficient of general term <m>x^{m-k-2}</m> to zero, 
        we get the recurrence relation.
        <me>
          (m-k)(m-k-1)a_{k}+\{n(n+1)-(m-k-2)(m-k-1)\}a_{k+2}=0
        </me>
        now,
        <me>
          n(n+1)-(m-k-2)(m-k-1) 
        </me>
        <me>
          =n^{2}+n-(m-k-1-1)(m-k-1) 
        </me>
        
        <me>
          =n^{2}+n-(m-k-1)^{2}+(m-k-1) 
        </me>
        <me>
          =(m-k+n-1)-\{(m-k-1)^{2}-n^{2}\}
        </me>
        
        <me>
          =(m-k+n-1)-(m-k-n-1)(m-k+n-1) 
        </me>
        <me>
          =-(m-k+n-1)[m-k-n-2]
        </me>
        
        or,
        <me>
          (m-k)(m-k-1)a_{k}-(m-k+n-1)(m-k-n-2)a_{k+2}=0
        </me>
        or,
        <men xml:id="eqn-leg_eq6">
          a_{k+2}=\frac{(m-k)(m-k-1)}{(m-k+n-1)(m-k-n-2)}a_{k}
        </men>
      </p>

      <paragraphs>
        <title>Case I</title>
        <p>
          For, <m>m=n</m>,
          <me>
            a_{k+2} = \frac{(n-k)(n-k-1)}{(n-k+n-1)(n-k-n-2)}a_{k}
          </me>
          <me>
            = - \frac{(n-k)(n-k-1)}{(2n-k-1)(k+2)}a_{k}
          </me>
          so that 
          <me>
            a_{2}=-\frac{n(n-1)}{(2n-1)\cdot 2}a_{o};
          </me>
          <me>
            a_{4}=\frac{(n-2)(n-3)}{(2n-3)\cdot 4}a_{2}=\frac{n(n-1)(n-2)(n-3)}{(2n-1)(2n-3)\cdot 4\cdot 2}a_{o}
          </me>
          and so on. Also 
          <me>
            a_{1}=a_{3}=a_{5}=\cdots =0.
          </me>
          Hence the series <xref ref="eqn-leg_eq2"/> becomes 
          <me>
            y=a_{o}\left[x^{n}-\frac{n(n-1)}{(2n-1)\cdot 2}x^{n-2}+\frac{n(n-1)(n-2)(n-3)}{(2n-1)(2n-3)\cdot 4\cdot 2}x^{n-4}-\cdots\right.
          </me>
          <me>
            +\left.(-1)^{r}\frac{n(n-1)(n-2)\cdots(n-2r+1)}{2\cdot 4\cdots 2r(2n-1)(2n-3)\cdots (2n-2r+1)}x^{n-2r}\right.
          </me>
          	<men xml:id="eqn-leg_eq7">
              \left.\cdots+\cdots\right]
            </men>
            <me>
              \therefore y=a_{o}x^{n}\left[1-\frac{n(n-1)}{(2n-1)\cdot 2}x^{-2}+\frac{n(n-1)(n-2)(n-3)}{(2n-1)(2n-3)\cdot 4\cdot 2}x^{-4}-\cdots\right.
            </me>
            <me>
               +\left.(-1)^{r}\frac{n(n-1)(n-2)\cdots(n-2r+1)}{2\cdot 4\cdots 2r(2n-1)(2n-3)\cdots (2n-2r+1)}x^{-2r}\right.
            </me>
            
            <men xml:id="eqn-leg_eq8">
             \left.\cdots +\cdots\right]
            </men>
            which is a solution of equation <xref ref="eqn-leg_eq1"/>. 
          </p>
          <p>
            If we choose the arbitrary constant <m>a_{o}=\frac{1\cdot 3\cdot 5\cdots (2n-1)}{n!}</m>	
            where <m>n</m> is a positive integer, then this solution of Legender's equation 
            is known as Legender's Polynomials or Legender's Function of First Kind, 
            <m>P_{n}(x)</m>, i.e., 
            <me>
              P_{n}(x) = \frac{1\cdot 3\cdot 5\cdots (2n-1)}{n!}\left[x^{n}-\frac{n(n-1)}{(2n-1)\cdot 2}x^{n-2} \right. 
            </me>
            <me>
             \left. +\frac{n(n-1)(n-2)(n-3)}{(2n-1)(2n-3)\cdot 4\cdot 2}x^{n-4}-\cdots\right.
            </me>
            <me>
              +\left.(-1)^{r}\frac{n(n-1)(n-2)\cdots(n-2r+1)}{2\cdot 4\cdots 2r(2n-1)(2n-3)\cdots (2n-2r+1)}x^{n-2r}\right.
            </me>
            
            <men xml:id="eqn-leg_eq9">
              \left.\cdots +\cdots\right] 
            </men>
            This is a terminating series. When <m>n</m> is even, <m> n=2r</m> and the last term is 
            <me>
              (-1)^{\frac{n}{2}}\frac{n(n-1)(n-2)\cdots 3\cdot 2\cdot 1}{(2n-1)(2n-3)\cdots (n+1)\cdot 2\cdot 4\cdot 6\cdots n}
            </me>
            when <m>n</m> is odd, <m>n=2r+1</m> and the last term is 
            <me>
              (-1)^{\frac{n-1}{2}}\frac{n(n-1)(n-2)\cdots 3\cdot 2\cdot 1}{(2n-1)(2n-3)\cdots (n+2)\cdot 2\cdot 4\cdot 6\cdots (n-1)}x
            </me>
              <m>P_{n}(x)</m> is that solution of Legender's equation which is equal 
              to unity when <m>x=1</m>.
            </p>
      </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Case II</title>
      <p>
        For, <m>m=-n-1,</m>  we have from equation <xref ref="eqn-leg_eq6"/>
        <me>
          a_{k+2} = \frac{(n+k+1)(n+k+2)}{(k+2)(2n+k+3)}a_{k}
        </me>
        so that 
        <me>
          a_{2}=-\frac{(n+1)(n+2)}{2(2n+3)}a_{o};
        </me>
        <me>
          a_{4}=\frac{(n+1)(n+2)(n+3)(n+4)}{2\cdot 4\cdot (2n+3)(2n+5)}a_{o} 
        </me>
        and so on. Also 
        ,<me>
          a_{1}=a_{3}=a_{5}=\cdots =0.
        </me>
        Hence,
        <me>
          y=a_{o}\left[x^{-n-1}+\frac{(n+1)(n+2)}{2(2n+3)}x^{-n-3} +\frac{(n+1)(n+2)(n+3)(n+4)}{2\cdot 4\cdot (2n+3)(2n+5)}x^{-n-5}+\right.
        </me>
        
        <men xml:id="eqn-leg_eq10">
          \left.\cdots+ \frac{(n+1)(n+2)(n+3)\cdots(n+2r)}{2\cdot 4\cdot 2r(2n+3)(2n+5)\cdots (2n+2r+1)}x^{-n-2r-1}+\cdots\right] 
        </men>
        <me>
          y=a_{o}x^{-n-1}\left[1+\frac{(n+1)(n+2)}{2(2n+3)}x^{-2}+\cdots \right.
        </me>
        <me>
          \left. + \frac{(n+1)(n+2)(n+3)\cdots(n+2r)}{2\cdot 4\cdot 2r(2n+3)(2n+5)\cdots (2n+2r+1)}x^{-2r}\right.
        </me>
        <men xml:id="eqn-leg_eq11">
          \left.\cdots +\cdots\right]
        </men>
        This gives an another solution of equation <xref ref="eqn-leg_eq1"/>. 
        If we choose, <m>a_{o}=\frac{n!}{1\cdot 3\cdot5 \cdots (2n+1)}</m>	
        where <m>n</m> is a positive integer, then this solution of equation 
        <xref ref="eqn-leg_eq1"/> is known as  Legender's Function of Second Kind, 
        <m>Q_{n}(x)</m>, i.e.,
        <me>
          Q_{n}(x) =\frac{n!}{1\cdot 3\cdot5 \cdots (2n+1)}\left[x^{-n-1}+\frac{(n+1)(n+2)}{2(2n+3)}x^{-n-3}+\cdots\right.
        </me>
        <men xml:id="eqn-leg_eq12">
          \left.\cdots+\frac{(n+1)(n+2)\cdots(n+2r)}{2\cdot 4\cdots2r\cdot(2n+3)\cdots(2n+2r+1)}x^{-n-2r-1}+\cdots\right]
        </men>
        This is a non - terminating series. The most general solution of  Legender's Equation is 
        <m>y=AP_{n}(x)+BQ_{n}(x)</m> where <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> are arbitrary constants.
        </p>
    </paragraphs>

  <paragraphs>
    <title>Note:</title>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          If the infinite series solution of a given differential equation is 
          reduced into a finite series, then the solution is called the polynomial. 
          "Polynomial is a finite series that consists of a finite number of terms. 
          Each term in a polynomial is a product of a coefficient, a variable raised 
          to a power, and there is a finite number of such terms in the polynomial expression. 
          The degree of the polynomial determines the highest power of the variable present 
          in the expression, and the number of terms is directly related to the degree".
          For a positive integer <m>n</m>,  equation <xref ref="eqn-leg_eq8"/> is a finite 
          series (polynomial) and  equation <xref ref="eqn-leg_eq10"/> is an infinite series. 
          For a nigative integer <m>n</m>,  equation <xref ref="eqn-leg_eq8"/> is an infinite 
          series and  equation <xref ref="eqn-leg_eq11"/> is a polynomial. The general solution 
          is a linear combination of a finite series and an infinite series.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          If we want to solve the Legender's  equation in a series of ascending powers 
          of <m>x</m>, we may proceed by taking  <m>y=\sum\limits_{k=0}^{\infty} a_{k}x^{m+k}</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          The expansion of <m>P_{n}(x)</m> can also be written as 
          <me>
            P_{n}(x) = \sum\limits_{r=0}^{N} (-1)^{r}\frac{1\cdot 3\cdot 5\cdots (2n-1)}{n!} 
          </me>
          <me>
             \times\frac{n(n-1)\cdots(n-2r+1)}{2\cdot 4\cdots 2r\cdot(2n-1)(2n-3)\cdots (2n-2r+1)}x^{n-2r}
          </me>
          
          <me>
            =\sum\limits_{r=0}^{N} (-1)^{r}\frac{1\cdot 3\cdot 5\cdots (2n-2r-1)}{2^{r}\cdot r! (n-2r)!}x^{n-2r}
          </me>
          <me>
            =\sum\limits_{r=0}^{N} (-1)^{r}\frac{1\cdot 2\cdot 3\cdot 5\cdots (2n-2r)}{2^{r}\cdot r! (n-2r)!\cdot 2\cdot 4\cdots (2n-2r)}x^{n-2r}
          </me>
          <men xml:id="eqn-leg_eq13">
            =\sum\limits_{r=0}^{N} (-1)^{r}\frac{1(2n-2r)!}{2^{r}\cdot r! (n-r)!(n-2r)!}x^{n-2r}
          </men>
          where <m>N=\frac{n}{2}</m> for <m>n</m> even and <m>N=n-\frac{1}{2}</m> for <m>n</m> odd. 
          In particular, 
          <me>
            P_{n}(x) = \frac{1\cdot 3\cdot 5\cdots (2n-1)}{n!}\left[x^{n}-\frac{n(n-1)}{2(2n-1)}x^{n-2}\right.
          </me>
          <me>
            \left.+\frac{n(n-1)(n-2)(n-3)}{2\cdot 4\cdots (2n-1)(2n-3)}x^{n-4}-\cdots\right]
          </me>
          
          <me>
            =\frac{2n)!}{(2\cdot 4\cdot 6 \cdots 2n)n!}\left[x^{n}-\frac{n(n-1)}{2(2n-1)}x^{n-2} \right.
          </me>
          <me>
            \left.+\frac{n(n-1)(n-2)(n-3)}{2\cdot 4\cdots (2n-1)(2n-3)}x^{n-4}-\cdots\right]
          </me>
          
          <me>
            =\frac{2n)!}{(2^{n}n!n!}\left[x^{n}-\frac{n(n-1)}{2(2n-1)}x^{n-2}\right.
          </me>
          <me>
            \left.+\frac{n(n-1)(n-2)(n-3)}{2\cdot 4\cdots (2n-1)(2n-3)}x^{n-4}-\cdots\right]
          </me>
          
          putting,	<m>n=0,1,2,3,\cdots</m>  etc., we get - <m>P_{n}(x)=1</m>.	
          <me>
            P_{1}(x)=\frac{2!}{2\cdot 1!\cdot1!}[x] =x,
          </me>
              other terms are vanished.
            <me>
              P_{2}(x)=\frac{4!}{2^{2}\cdot 2!\cdot 2!}[x^{2}-\frac{1}{3}] = \frac{3}{2}(x^{2}-\frac{1}{3}) = \frac{3x^{2}-1}{2},
            </me>
             other terms are vanished.
            <me>
              P_{3}(x)=\frac{6!}{2^{3}\cdot 3!\cdot 3!}[x^{3}-\frac{3}{2}\frac{2}{5}x] = \frac{5x^{3}-3x}{2},
            </me>
               etc.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          From expression <xref ref="eqn-leg_eq13"/>, we deduce that
          <me>
            P_{n}(x) =\sum\limits_{r=0}^{N}\frac{ (-1)^{r} }{2^{n}r!(n-r)!}\frac{d^{n}}{dx^{n}}(x^{2n-2r}) 
          </me>
          <me>
             =\frac{1}{2^{n}n!}\frac{d^{n}}{dx^{n}}\sum\limits_{r=0}^{N}(-1)^{r}\frac{n!}{r!(n-r)!}x^{2n-2r} 
          </me>
          
          <me>
            \left[ \because   \frac{d^{n}}{dx^{n}}x^{2n-2r} = \frac{(2n-2r)!}{(n-2r)!}x^{2n-2r}\right]
          </me>
          Now extended the upper limit from <m>N</m> to <m>n</m> since the extra terms from 
          <m>N+1</m> to <m>n</m> do not contribute anything because each term in the series 
          <me>
            \sum\limits_{r=N+1}^{n} \frac{d^{n}}{dx^{n}}\frac{(-1)^{r}n!}{r!(n-r)!}x^{2n-2r}
          </me>
          vanishes for <m>r</m> and <m>n</m> integrals. Also, 
          <me>
             (x^{2}-1)^{n}=  \sum\limits_{r=0}^{n} \frac{(-1)^{r}n!}{r!(n-r)!}x^{2(n-r)} 
          </me>
          from Binomial expansion of <m>(x^{2}-1)^{n}</m>
          <me>
            \therefore \quad P_{n}(x) = \frac{1}{2^{n}n!}\frac{d^{n}}{dx^{n}}(x^{2}-1)^{n}
          </me>
          This is the Rodrigue's Formula for Legender's Polynomial.	
          The plot for Legender's polynomial is shown in <xref ref="fig-fig43"/>.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </paragraphs>
  </introduction>
 
 
<subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-legn_rodrg">
  <title>Rodrigue's Formula</title>
  <p>
    <me>
      P_{n}(x) = \frac{1}{2^{n}n!}\frac{d^{n}}{dx^{n}}(x^{2}-1)^{n}
    </me>
    </p>
    <proof>
      <p>
    Let 
    <men xml:id="eqn-rodrg_legn1">
      v=(x^{2}-1)^{n}
    </men>
     then,
    <me>
      \frac{\,dv}{\,dx}=n(x^{2}-1)^{n-1}\cdot2x  =\frac{n(x^{2}-1)^{n}}{(x^{2}-1)}\cdot 2x 
    </me>
    or,
    <me>
      (x^{2}-1)\frac{\,dv}{\,dx}=2n(x^{2}-1)^{n}x
    </me>
    or,
    <men xml:id="eqn-rodrg_legn2">
      (x^{2}-1)\frac{\,dv}{\,dx} =2nvx
    </men>
    Now, differentiating equation <xref ref="eqn-rodrg_legn2"/>, <m>(n+1)</m> times using 
    Leibnitz theorem, we get - 
    <me>
      (x^{2}-1)\frac{d^{n+2}}{dx^{n+2}}v + \comb{n+1}{1} (2x)\frac{d^{n+1}}{dx^{n+1}}v+\comb{n+1}{2} (2)\frac{d^{n}}{dx^{n}}v
    </me>
    <me>
      =2n\left[x	\frac{d^{n+1}}{dx^{n+1}}v+\comb{n+1}{1}(1)\frac{d^{n}}{dx^{n}}\right].
    </me>
    
    or,
    <me>
      (x^{2}-1)\frac{d^{n+2}}{dx^{n+2}}v +2x\left[\comb{n+1}{1} -n\right]\frac{d^{n+1}}{dx^{n+1}}v
    </me>
    <me>
      +2\left[\comb{n+1}{2} -n \comb{n+1}{1}\right]\frac{d^{n}}{dx^{n}}v=0
    </me>
    
    or,
    <men xml:id="eqn-rodrg_legn3">
       (x^{2}-1)\frac{d^{n+2}}{dx^{n+2}}v +2x \frac{d^{n+1}}{dx^{n+1}}v-n(n+1)\frac{d^{n}v}{dx^{n}}=0
    </men>
    If we put <m>\frac{d^{n}v}{dx^{n}}=y</m> then equation <xref ref="eqn-rodrg_legn3"/> becomes
    <me>
      (x^{2}-1)\frac{d^{2}y}{dx^{2}} +2x \frac{dy}{dx}-n(n+1)y=0
    </me>
    or,
    <men xml:id="eqn-rodrg_legn4">
      (1-x^{2})\frac{d^{2}y}{dx^{2}} -2x \frac{dy}{dx}+n(n+1)y=0.	
    </men>
    which is Legendre's equation and <m>y=  \frac{d^{n}v}{dx^{n}}</m>  is one of its solution.
    <men xml:id="eqn-rodrg_legn5">
     \therefore P_{n}(x)=C\frac{d^{n}v}{dx^{n}}
    </men>
    where C is a constant. But,
    <me>
      v=(x^{2}-1)^{n}=(x+1)^{n}(x-1)^{n},
    </me>
    so that 
    <me>
      \frac{d^{n}v}{dx^{n}}=(x+1)^{n}\frac{d^{n}}{dx^{n}}(x-1)^{n}+\comb{n}{1}n(x+1)^{n-1}\frac{d^{n-1}}{dx^{n-1}}(x-1)^{n}
    </me>
    <me>
      +\cdots+(x-1)^{n}\frac{d^{n}}{dx^{n}}(x+1)^{n}.
    </me>
    when <m>x=1</m>, 
    <me>
      \frac{d^{n}v}{dx^{n}}=2^{n}n!
    </me>
    All the other terms disappear as <m>(x-1)</m> is a factor in every term except first. 
    <fn>
    <me>
      \because \frac{d^{n}}{dx^{n}}(x-1)^{n}=n! ; 
    </me>
    <me>
      \frac{d^{n-1}}{dx^{n-1}}(x-1)^{n}=n(x-1)\cdots 2(x-1); 
    </me>
    <me>
      \frac{d^{n-2}}{dx^{n-2}}(x-1)^{n}=n(x-1)\cdots 3(x-1)^{2}
    </me>
    </fn>
    Therefore, when <m>x=1</m>, equation <xref ref="eqn-rodrg_legn5"/> gives
    <me>
       P_{n}(1) = C\cdot 2^{n}n!=1 \quad \therefore C =\frac{1}{2^{n}n!}
    </me>
    Hence, 
    <me>
      P_{n}(x) = \frac{1}{2^{n}n!}\frac{d^{n}v}{dx^{n}}	
    </me>
    from equation <xref ref="eqn-rodrg_legn5"/>.
    <me>
      \therefore \quad P_{n}(x) = \frac{1}{2^{n}n!}\frac{d^{n}}{dx^{n}}(x^{2}-1)^{n}
    </me>
    from equation <xref ref="eqn-rodrg_legn1"/>. This is the Rodrigue's Formula for Legendre Polynomial.
    </p>
    </proof>
</subsubsection>


<subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-legnd">
  <title>Legendre Polynomials</title>
   <figure xml:id="fig-fig43">
    <caption>Legendre's Polynomial</caption>
    <image source="fig43.png" width ="35%"/>
</figure>
  <p>
   The Rodrigue's formula for Legendre's Polynomials is 
   <me>
    P_{n}(x) = \frac{1}{2^{n}n!}\frac{d^{n}}{dx^{n}}(x^{2}-1)^{n}
   </me>
   If <m>n=0</m>,  
   <me>
    P_{o}(x) = \frac{1}{2^{0}0!}=1
   </me>
   If <m>n=1</m>, 
   <me>
    P_{1}(x) = \frac{1}{2^{1}1!}\frac{d}{dx}(x^{2}-1)=\frac{1}{2}(2x)=x.
   </me>
   If <m>n=2</m>, 
   <me>
     P_{2}(x) = \frac{1}{2^{2}2!}\frac{d^{2}}{dx^{2}}(x^{2}-1)^{2}
   </me>
   <me>
     =\frac{1}{8}\frac{d}{dx}[2(x^{2}-1)(2x)] = \frac{1}{2}[2(x^{2}\cdot 1+2x\cdot x]
   </me>
   <me>
    =\frac{1}{2}[3x^{2}-1]
   </me>
    similarly, 
    <me>
      P_{3}(x) = \frac{1}{2}(5x^{3}-3x)
    </me>
   <me>
    P_{4}(x) = \frac{1}{8}(35x^{4}-30x^{2}+3)
   </me>
   <me>
    P_{5}(x) = \frac{1}{8}(63x^{5}-70x^{2}+15x)
   </me>
   <me>
     \vdots  \hspace{4cm}  \vdots
   </me>
 <me>
   P_{n}(x) =\sum\limits_{r=0}^{N}(-1)^{r} \frac{(2n-2r)!}{2^{n}r!(n-r)!(n-2r)!}x^{n-2r};
 </me>
 where, 
 <me>
  N = \quad \begin{cases} 
  \frac{n}{2}, \quad \text{if n is even.}\\ 
  \frac{1}{2}(n-1),\quad \text{if n is odd.} 
	\end{cases}	
 </me>
 </p>

<p>
 <alert>Note:</alert>
 we can evaluate <m>P_{n}(x)</m> by expanding <m>(x^{2}-1)^{n}</m> from Binomial theorem.
 <me>
  (x^{2}-1)^{n}=\sum\limits_{r=0}^{n}{\comb{n}{r}(x^{2})^{n-r}(-1)^{r}}
 </me>
 <me>
  =	\sum\limits_{r=0}^{n}(-1)^{r}\frac{n!}{r!(n-r)!}(x^{2n-2r})
 </me>
 
 However,
 <me>
  P_{n}(x) = \frac{1}{2^{n}n!}\frac{d^{n}}{dx^{n}}(x^{2}-1)^{n}=\frac{1}{2^{n}n!}\sum\limits_{r=0}^{n}\frac{n!}{r!(n-r)!}\frac{d^{n}}{dx^{n}}(x^{2n-2r})
 </me>
<me>
  =\sum\limits_{r=0}^{n}(-1)^{r}\frac{(2n-2r)!}{2^{n}r!(n-r)!(n-2r)!}x^{n-2r}
</me> 
  The last term contains either <m>x^{0}</m> or <m>x^{1}</m>. 
  <me>
     \therefore \quad n-2r = 0
  </me>
  or,
  <me>
    r=\frac{n}{2}  \quad	\text{(for n even)}
  </me>
  or,
  <me>
     n-2r=1 
  </me>
  or,
  <me>
    r =\frac{1}{2}(n-1) \quad \text{(for n odd)}.
  </me>
 </p>
<paragraphs>
  <title>Python Code:</title>
  <p>import numpy as np </p>
  <p> from scipy.special import eval_legendre </p>
 <p> import matplotlib.pyplot as plt </p>
 <p> from scipy.linalg import det </p>

<p> N = range(0, 6) </p>
<p>eval_legendre(N, 0) </p>

<p> X = np.linspace(-1, 1)</p>

<p> for n in range(0, 6):  </p>
 <p>   y = eval_legendre(n, X)  </p>
 <p>   plt.plot(X, y, label=r'$P_{}(x)$'.format(n))  </p>
  <p>  plt.title("Legendre Polynomials")  </p>
    <p>plt.xlabel("x")  </p>
    <p> plt.ylabel(r'$P_n(x)$')  </p>
   <p> plt.legend(loc='lower right')  </p>
     <p> plt.show()  </p>
  
</paragraphs>
 
</subsubsection>

<subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-genrt_legn">
  <title>Generating Function for <m>P_{n}(x)</m></title>
  <idx><h>generating function</h></idx>
  <p>
    Legendre Polynomial <m>P_{n}(x)</m> is the coefficient of <m>z^{n}</m> in 
    <m>(1-2xz+z^{2})^{-\frac{1}{2}}</m>, i.e., 
    <men xml:id="eqn-legn_gen1">
     (1-2xz+z^{2})^{-\frac{1}{2}} =\sum\limits_{n=0}^{\infty}P_{n}(x)z^{n} 
    </men>
      </p>

    <proof>
      <p>
        We have  
        <me>
          (1-2xz+z^{2})^{-\frac{1}{2}} =\left[1-z(2x-z)\right]^{-\frac{1}{2}}
        </me>
        <me>
          =1+\frac{1}{2}z(2x-z)+\frac{(-\frac{1}{2})(-\frac{3}{2})}{2!}z^{2}(2x-z)^{2}+\cdots
        </me>
        <me>
         +\cdots \frac{(-\frac{1}{2})(-\frac{3}{2})(-\frac{5}{2})\cdots(-\frac{1}{2}-n+1)}{n!}(-z)^{n}(2x-z)^{n}+\cdots 
        </me>
        <me>
          =1+\frac{1}{2}z(2x-z)+\frac{1\cdot 3}{2^{2}2!}z^{2}(2x-z)^{2}+
        </me>
        <me>
          \cdots+\frac{1\cdot 3\cdot 5\cdots(2n-5)}{2^{n-2}(n-2)!}z^{n-2}(2x-z)^{n-2}
        </me>
        <me>
           + \frac{1\cdot 3\cdot 5\cdots(2n-3)}{2^{n-1}(n-1)!}z^{n-1}(2x-z)^{n-1}
        </me>
        <men xml:id="eqn-legn_gen2">
         +\frac{1\cdot 3\cdot 5\cdots(2n-1)}{2^{n}(n)!}z^{n}(2x-z)^{n}+\cdots
        </men>
        <fn>
        <me>
          \left[\because (1-x)^{n}= 1-nx+\frac{n(n-1)}{2!}x^{2}-\frac{n(n-1)(n-2)}{3!}x^{2}+\cdots\right]
        </me>
        <me>
         \left[\because (x+y)^{n}= x^{n}+\comb{n}{1}x^{n-1}y+\comb{n}{2}x^{n-2}y^{2}+\cdots\right]
        </me>
        </fn>
        But,
        <me>
          z^{n}(2x-z)^{n}=z^{n}(2x^{n}+\cdots 
        </me>
        <me>
          z^{n-1}(2x-z)^{n-1}=z^{n-1}\left[(2x)^{n-1}-\comb{n-1}{1}(2x)^{n-2}z+\cdots\right] 
        </me>
        <me>
          = z^{n-1}(2x)^{n-1}-(n-1)(2x)^{n-2}z^{n}+\cdots 
        </me>
        and 
        <me>
          z^{n-2}(2x-z)^{n-2}
        </me>
        <me>
          =z^{n-2}\left[(2x)^{n-2}-\comb{n-2}{1}(2x)^{n-3}z+\cdots+\comb{n-2}{2}(2x)^{n-4}z^{2}+\cdots\right]
        </me>
        <me>
           =z^{n-2}(2x)^{n-2}-(n-2)(2x)^{n-3}z^{n-1}+\frac{(n-2)(n-3)}{2!}(2x)^{n-4}z^{n}+\cdots
        </me>
        Hence, replacing by these values to collect the coefficient of <m>z^{n}</m>, we get - 
        <me>
          (1-2xz+z^{2})^{-\frac{1}{2}}=1+xz+\left(\frac{3}{2}x^{2}-\frac{1}{2}\right)z^{2}+\cdots
        </me>
        <me>
          \cdots+\left[\frac{1\cdot3\cdot5\cdots(2n-1)}{2^{n}n!}2^{n}x^{n}-\frac{1\cdot3\cdot5\cdots(2n-3)}{2^{n-1}(n-1)!}(n-1)(2x)^{n-2}\right.
        </me>
        <me>
          +\left.\frac{1\cdot3\cdot5\cdots(2n-5)(n-2)(n-3)}{2^{n-2}(n-2)!2!}2^{n-4}x^{n-4}\right]z^{n}+\cdots
        </me>
        <me>
          =1+xz+\frac{1}{2}(3x^{2}-1)z^{2}+\cdots
        </me>
        <me>
          +\frac{1\cdot3\cdot5\cdots(2n-1)}{n!}\left[x^{n}-\frac{n(n-1)}{2(2n-1)}x^{n-2}\right.
        </me>
        <me>
          \left. +\frac{n(n-1)(n-2)(n-3)}{2\cdot4(2n-1)(2n-3)}x^{n-4}+\cdots\right]z^{n}+\cdots
        </me>
        
        <me>
          =P_{o}(x)+P_{1}(x)z+P_{2}(x)z^{2}+\cdots+P_{n}(x)z^{n}+\cdots =\sum\limits_{n=0}^{\infty}P_{n}(x)z^{n}
        </me>
      </p>
      <p>
        Thus the function <m> (1-2xz+z^{2})^{-\frac{1}{2}}</m> is defined as generating function 
        of <m>P_{n}(x) </m>.
        </p>
    </proof>
  
</subsubsection>


<subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-Legn_import">
  <title>Some Important Results</title>
  <ol marker="i.">
    <li>
      <p>
       <me>
        P_{n}(1) =1
       </me>
        We know that	<m>(1-2xz+z^{2})^{-\frac{1}{2}} </m> 
        <me>
          =1+zP_{1}(x)+z^{2}P_{2}(x)+z^{3}P_{3}(x)+\cdots+z^{n}P_{n}(x)+\cdots
        </me>
        
        substituting <m> '1'</m> for  <m>'x'</m> in the above equation, we get -
        <me>
          (1-2xz+z^{2})^{-\frac{1}{2}} 
        </me>
        <me>
          =1+zP_{1}(1)+z^{2}P_{2}(1)+z^{3}P_{3}(1)+\cdots+z^{n}P_{n}(1)+\cdots
        </me>
        
        or,
        <me>
          \left[(1-z)^{2}\right]^{-\frac{1}{2}}=\sum\limits_{n=0}^{\infty}z^{n}P_{n}(1)
        </me>
        or,
        <me>
          (1-z)^{-1}=\sum\limits_{n=0}^{\infty}z^{n}P_{n}(1)
        </me>
        <me>
         \sum\limits_{n=0}^{\infty}z^{n}P_{n}(1)=(1-z)^{-1} =1+z+z^{2}+z^{3}+\cdots+z^{n}+\cdots
        </me>
        Equating the coefficients of <m> z^{n}</m> on both sides, we get -
        <me>
          P_{n}(1) =1.
        </me>      
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        <me>
           P_{n}(-1) =(-1)^{n}P_{n}
        </me>
        putting <m>x=-1</m> in the generating function of <m>P_{n}(x)</m>, we get - 
        <me>
          (1+2z+z^{2})^{-\frac{1}{2}} =\sum\limits_{n=0}^{\infty}z^{n}P_{n}(-1)z^{n}
        </me>
        or,
        <me>
          \sum\limits_{n=0}^{\infty}z^{n}P_{n}(-1)z^{n}=(1+z)^{-1}=\sum\limits_{n=0}^{\infty}(-1)^{n}z^{n}
        </me>
        equating the coefficient of <m>z^{n}</m>, we get - 
        <me>
          P_{n}(-1)=(-1)^{n},
        </me>
        i.e.,
        <me>
           P_{n}(-1)=(-1)^{n}P_{n}(1)
        </me>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        <me>
          P_{n}(-x) =(-1)^{n} P_{n}(x)
        </me>
        we have 
        <me>
          (1-2xz+z^{2})^{-\frac{1}{2}} 
        </me>
        <me>
          =[1-2(-x)(-z)+(-z)^{2}]^{-\frac{1}{2}}=\sum\limits_{n=0}^{\infty}P_{n}(-x)(-z)^{n}
        </me>
        
        now replacing <m>x</m> by <m>-x</m> and <m>z</m> by <m>-z</m>.
        <me>
          \sum\limits_{n=0}^{\infty}P_{n}(x)(z)^{n}=\sum\limits_{n=0}^{\infty}(-1)^{n}P_{n}(-x)(z)^{n}
        </me>
          equating the coefficients of <m>z^{n}</m>, we get - 
          <me>
            P_{n}(x)=(-1)^{n}P_{n}(-x) 
          </me>
          <me>
            P_{n}(-x)=(-1)^{n}P_{n}(x)
          </me>
      </p>
      <p>
        <term>Alternative:</term>
       We know that 
       <me>
        P_{n}(x)= \sum\limits_{r=0}^{N}(-1)^{r}\frac{(2n-2r)!}{2^{n}r!(n-r)!(n-2r)}(x)^{n-2r};
       </me>
       <me>
        \begin{cases} 
        \text{where}\quad N=\frac{n}{2} \quad \text{for n even}\\ 
        \quad =\frac{n-1}{2} \quad \text{for n odd}\end{cases}
       </me>
          Thus
          <me>
             P_{n}(-x) = \sum\limits_{r=0}^{N}(-1)^{r}\frac{(2n-2r)!}{2^{n}r!(n-r)!(n-2r)}(-1)^{n-2r}(x)^{n-2r}
          </me>
            <me>
              =(-1)^{n}\sum\limits_{r=0}^{N}(-1)^{r}\frac{(2n-2r)!}{2^{n}r!(n-r)!(n-2r)}(x)^{n-2r}
            </me>
            <me>
              =(-1)^{n}P_{n}(x)
            </me>
      </p>
    </li>
  </ol>
</subsubsection>

<subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-legn_recurrnc">
  <title>Recurrence Relations for <m>P_{n}(x)</m></title>
  <p>
    Recurrence relations are the relationship among the polynomials of different orders 
    and their derivatives of differential orders. 
     </p>
    <ol marker ="I.">
      <li>
        <p>
          <me>
            nP_{n}=(2n-1)xP_{n-1}-(n-1)P_{n-2}.
          </me>
          Solution: We know that 
          <me>
            (1-2xz+z^{2})^{-\frac{1}{2}}=\sum z^{n}[P_{n}(x)]
          </me>
          Differentiating it with respect to <m>z</m>, we get - 
          <me>
            -\frac{1}{2}(1-2xz+z^{2})^{-\frac{3}{2}}(-2x+2z)=\sum n z^{n-1}P_{n}(x)
          </me>
          or,
          <me>
            (1-2xz+z^{2})^{-\frac{1}{2}}(x-z)=(1-2xz+z^{2})\sum n z^{n-1}P_{n}(x)
          </me>
          or,
          <me>
            (x-z)\sum z^{n}P_{n}(x)=(1-2xz+z^{2})\sum nz^{n-1}P_{n}(x)
          </me>
          Equating the coefficient of <m>z^{n-1}</m> on both sides, we get-
          <me>
            xP_{n-1}-P_{n-2}=nP_{n}-2x(n-1)P_{n-1}+(n-2)P_{n-2}
          </me>
          or,
          <me>
            nP_{n}=(2n-1)xP_{n-1}-(n-1)P_{n-2}
          </me>
          <term>Note:</term>
          If <m>n-1=m </m>, then this result reduces to 
          <me>
            (m+1)P_{m+1}(x)=(2M+1)xP_{m}(x)-mP_{m-1}(x).
          </me>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <me>
             xP'_{n} - P'_{n-1}=n P_{n} 
          </me>  
          Solution: We know that
          <men xml:id="eqn-legn_genfn1">
            (1-2xz+z^{2})^{-\frac{1}{2}}=\sum z^{n}[P_{n}(x)]
          </men>
          Differentiating equation <xref ref="eqn-legn_genfn1"/> with respect to <m>z</m>, we get - 
          <me>
            -\frac{1}{2}(1-2xz+z^{2})^{-\frac{3}{2}}(-2x+2z)=\sum n z^{n-1}P_{n}(x)
          </me>
          or,
          <men xml:id="eqn-legn_genfn2">
            (x-z)(1-2xz+z^{2})^{-\frac{3}{2}}=\sum nz^{n-1}P_{n}(x)
          </men>
          Differentiating equation <xref ref="eqn-legn_genfn1"/> with respect to <m>x</m>, we get - 
          <me>
            -\frac{1}{2}(1-2xz+z^{2})^{-\frac{3}{2}}=\sum  z^{n}P'_{n}(x)
          </me>
          or,
          <men xml:id="eqn-legn_genfn3">
            z(1-2xz+z^{2})^{-\frac{3}{2}}=\sum z^{n}P'_{n}(x)
          </men>
          Dividing equation <xref ref="eqn-legn_genfn2"/> by equation <xref ref="eqn-legn_genfn3"/>, 
          we get -
          <me>
            \frac{(x-z)}{z}=\frac{\sum nz^{n-1}P_{n}(x)}{\sum z^{n}P'_{n}(x)}
          </me>
            or,
            <me>
              (x-z)\sum z^{n}P'_{n}(x)=\sum nz^{n}P_{n}(x)
            </me>
              equating the coefficients of <m>z^{n} </m> from both sides, we get - 
              <me>
                xP'_{n}(x)-P'_{n-1}(x)=nP_{n}(x)
              </me>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <me>
            P'_{n}-xP'_{n-1} = nP_{n-1}.
          </me>
            solution: From relation I, we have -
            <me>
              nP_{n}=(2n-1)xP_{n-1}-(n-1)P_{n-2}
            </me>
            Differentiating this with respect to <m>x</m>, we get - 
            <me>
              n P'_{n}=(2n-1)P_{n-1}+(2n-1)xP'_{n-1}-(n-1)P'_{n-2}
            </me>
            or,
            <me>
              n\left[P'_{n}-xP'_{n-1}\right]-(n-1)\left[xP'_{n-1}-P'_{n-2}\right]=(2n-1)P_{n-1}
            </me>
            or,
            <me>
              n\left[P'_{n}-xP'_{n-1}\right]-(n-1)\left[(n-1)P_{n-1}\right]=(2n-1)P_{n-1}
            </me>
            from relation II. or,
            <me>
              n\left[P'_{n}-xP'_{n-1}\right]=\left[(n-1)^{2}+(2n-1)\right]P_{n-1} 
            </me>
            <me>
              =\left[n^{2}-2n+1+2n-1\right]P_{n-1} = n^{2}P_{n-1}
            </me>
            
            <me>
               \therefore \quad P'_{n}-xP'_{n-1}=nP_{n-1}.
            </me>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <me>
            P'_{n+1}-P'_{n-1}=(2n+1)P_{n}. 
          </me>
          Solution:	From relation I., we have 
          <me>
            nP_{n}=(2n-1)x P_{n-1}-(n-1)P_{n-2}
          </me>
          replacing <m>n</m> by (n+1), we get- 
          <me>
            (n+1)P_{n+1}=(2n+1)xP_{n}-nP_{n-1}
          </me>
              Differentiating this with respect to  <m>x</m>, we get -
              <me>
                (n+1)P'_{n+1}=(2n+1)P_{n}(2n+1)xP'_{n}-nP'_{n-1}
              </me>
              <me>
                =(2n+1)P_{n}+(2n+1)\left[nP_{n}+P'_{n-1}\right]-nP'_{n-1}
              </me>
              from relation II. Or,
              <me>
                (n+1)P'_{n+1}-(n+1)P'_{n-1}=(2n+1)(1+n)P_{n}
              </me>
                or,
                <me>
                  P'_{n+1}-P'_{n-1}=(2n+1)P_{n} 
                </me>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <me>
             (x^{2}-1)P'_{n}=n\left[xP_{n}-P_{n-1}\right]
          </me>
          Solution: From relation III, we have 
          <men xml:id="eqn-legn_genfn4">
            P'_{n}-xP'_{n-1}=nP_{n-1}
          </men>
          From relation II, we have 
           <men xml:id="eqn-legn_genfn5">
            xP'_{n}-P'_{n-1}=nP_{n}
          </men>
              multiplying equation <xref ref="eqn-legn_genfn5"/> by <m>x</m> and subtracting 
              from equation <xref ref="eqn-legn_genfn4"/>, we get - 
              <me>
                (1-x^{2})P'_{n}=n(P_{n-1}-xP_{n}) 
              </me>			
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <me>
            (x^{2}-1)P'_{n}=(n+1)\left[P_{n+1}-xP_{n}\right] 
          </me>
          Solution: From relation I, we have 
          <me>
            nP_{n}=(2n-1)xP_{n-1}-(n-1)P_{n-2}
          </me>
          Replacing <m>n</m> by <m>n+1</m>, we get - 
          <me>
            (n+1)P_{n+1}=(2n+1)xP_{n}-nP_{n-1}
          </me>
            or,
            <me>
              (n+1)\left[P_{n+1}-xP_{n}\right] =n\left[xP_{n}-P_{n-1}\right]
            </me>
              or,
              <me>
                (n+1)\left[P_{n+1}-xP_{n}\right] +n\left[P_{n-1}-xP_{n}\right]=0
              </me>
              or,
              <me>
                (n+1)\left[P_{n+1}-xP_{n}\right] +(1-x^{2})P'_{n}=0
              </me>
              <me>
                \therefore \quad (x^{2}-1)P'_{n}=(n+1)\left[P_{n+1}-xP_{n}\right] 
              </me>
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>

</subsubsection>

<subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-legn_orth">
  <title>Orthogonality of Legendre's Polynomials</title>
  <p>
    Legendre's polynomiala are a set of orthogonal functions in the interval <m>(-1,1)</m>.
    <men xml:id="eqn-legn_orth1">
      \int\limits_{-1}^{+1}P_{m}(x)P_{n}(x)\,dx=\frac{2}{2n+1}\,\delta_{m,n};
    </men>
    where
    <me>
       \delta_{m,n}=\begin{cases} 
       0 \quad \text{if}\quad  m \neq n \\ 
       1 \quad \text{if}\quad  m=n 
       \end{cases} 
       </me>
        here <m>\delta_{m,n} </m> is a Kronecker delta symbol and <m>m</m> and 
        <m>n</m> are positive integer. 
          </p>
        <proof>
          <p>
           <m>P_{n}(x)</m>  is a solution of 
             <men xml:id="eqn-legn_orth2">
          (1-x^{2})\frac{d^{2}y}{dx^{2}}-2x\frac{\,dy}{\,dx}+n(n+1) y =0
        </men>
        <m>P_{m}(x)</m>	 is a solution of 
        <men xml:id="eqn-legn_orth3">
        (1-x^{2})\frac{d^{2}z}{dx^{2}}-2x\frac{dz}{dx}+m(m+1) z =0	
        </men>
         Multiplying equation <xref ref="eqn-legn_orth2"/> by 'z' and equation 
        <xref ref="eqn-legn_orth3"/> by 'y' and then subtracte, we get -
         <me>
        (1-x^{2})\left[z\frac{d^{2}y}{dx^{2}}-y\frac{d^{2}z}{dx^{2}}\right]-2x\left[z\frac{\,dy}{\,dx}-y\frac{\,dz}{\,dx}\right]
       </me>
       <me>
        +\left[n(n+1)-m(m+1)\right]y z =0
       </me>
       
       or,
       <me>
        \frac{\,d}{\,dx}\left[(1-x^{2})\left\{z\frac{\,dy}{\,dx}-y\frac{\,dz}{\,dx}\right\}\right]+(n-m)(n+m+1)yz =0
       </me>
       Integrating with respect to <m>x</m> from -1 to +1, we get -
       <me>
        \left[(1-x^{2})\left(z\frac{dy}{dx}-y\frac{dz}{dx}\right)\right]^{1}_{-1}+(n-m)(n+m+1)\int\limits_{-1}^{+1}yz\,dx = 0 
       </me>
       or,
       <men xml:id="eqn-legn_orth4">
        0+(n-m)(n+m+1)\int\limits_{-1}^{+1}yz\,dx = 0
       </men>
       or,
       <me>
        \int\limits_{-1}^{+1}P_{m}(x)P_{n}(x)\,dx=0\quad \text{if}\quad m \neq n.
       </me>
          since <m>P_{n}(x)</m>  satisfies equation <xref ref="eqn-legn_orth2"/> 
          and <m>P_{m}(x)</m>  satisfies equation <xref ref="eqn-legn_orth3"/>.
          <men xml:id="eqn-legn_orth5">
            \therefore \quad \int\limits_{-1}^{+1}P_{m}(x)P_{n}(x)\,dx=0
          </men>
              If <m>m=n</m>, then equation <xref ref="eqn-legn_orth4"/> has zero on 
              both its sides and hence we can not get the value of integral for <m>m=n</m> 
              from this equation. To calculate the integral in such a case we may proceed 
              from generating function as <m>(1-2xz+z^{2})^{-\frac{1}{2}}=\sum z^{n}P_{n}(x)</m>. 
              Squaring both sides, we get -
              <me>
                	(1-2xz+z^{2})^{-1}=\sum [z^{n}P_{n}(x)]^{2}=\sum[P_{n}(x)]^{2}z^{2n}
              </me>
                Integrating with respect to <m>x</m> from -1 to +1, we get -
                <me>
                  \int\limits_{-1}^{+1}\frac{dx}{(1-2xz+z^{2})}=\sum\int\limits_{-1}^{+1}[P_{n}(x)]^{2}z^{2n}\,dx
                </me>
                or,
                <me>
                  \sum z^{2n}	\int\limits_{-1}^{+1}[P_{n}(x)]^{2}\,dx=\int\limits_{-1}^{+1}\frac{dx}{(1-2xz+z^{2})}\times\frac{-2z}{-2z} 
                </me>
                <me>
                   =-\frac{1}{2z}\left[\log(1-2xz+z^{2})\right]_{-1}^{+1} =-\frac{1}{2z}\log\frac{1-2z+z^{2}}{1+2z+z^{2}}
                </me>
                  <me>
                    =-\frac{1}{2z}\log\left(\frac{1-z}{1+z}\right)^{2} =\frac{1}{z}\log\left(\frac{1+z}{1-z}\right) =\frac{1}{z}[\log(1+z)-\log(1-z)]
                  </me>
                  <me>
                    =\frac{1}{z}\left[(z-\frac{z^{2}}{2}+\frac{z^{3}}{3}-\frac{z^{4}}{4}+\cdots)-(-z-\frac{z^{2}}{2}-\frac{z^{3}}{3}-\frac{z^{4}}{4}-\cdots)\right]
                  </me>
                  <me>
                    =\frac{2}{z}\left[z+\frac{z^{3}}{3}+\frac{z^{5}}{5}+\cdots\right]
                  </me>
                  <me>
                    =\frac{2}{z}\left[\sum\limits_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{z^{2n+1}}{2n+1}\right]=2\sum \frac{z^{2n}}{2n+1}
                  </me>
                  <me>
                    \therefore \quad \sum z^{2n}\int\limits_{-1}^{+1}[P_{n}(x)]^{2}\,dx=2\sum\frac{z^{2n}}{2n+1}.
                  </me>
                    Equating the coefficient of <m>z^{2n}</m> on both sides, we get - 
                    <men xml:id="eqn-legn_orth6">
                      \int\limits_{-1}^{+1}[P_{n}(x)]^{2}\,dx=\frac{2}{2n+1}
                    </men>
                    Now, from equation <xref ref="eqn-legn_orth5"/> and equation 
                    <xref ref="eqn-legn_orth6"/>, we have 
                    <me>
                      \int\limits_{-1}^{+1}P_{m}(x)\cdot P_{n}(x)\,dx	=\frac{2}{2n+1}\delta_{m,n};
                    </me>
                    where
                    <me>
                      \delta_{m,n}=\begin{cases} 
                      0 \quad \text{for}\quad  m \neq n \\
                      1 \quad \text{for}\quad  m=n 
                      \end{cases}
                    </me>
          </p>
        </proof>
      
</subsubsection>

<subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-legn_assoc">
  <title>The Associated Legendre's Polynomials</title>
  <p>
    <idx><h>Associated Legendre's Polynomials</h></idx> 
    Laplace's equation in spherical polar coordinates is given by	<m>\nabla^{2}\psi=0</m>. Or,
    <me>
      \frac{1}{r^{2}\sin\theta}\left[\sin\theta\frac{\partial}{\partial r}\left(r^{2}\frac{\partial\psi}{\partial r}\right)+\frac{\partial}{\partial \theta}\left(\sin\theta\frac{\partial\psi}{\partial \theta}\right)+\frac{1}{\sin\theta}\frac{\partial^{2}\psi}{\partial\phi^{2}}\right]=0
    </me>
      [see Laplacian in spherical curvilinear coordinates <xref ref="subsec-spher_cord"/>]
      or,
      <me>
        \frac{1}{r^{2}}\frac{\partial}{\partial r}\left(r^{2}\frac{\partial\psi}{\partial r}\right)+\frac{1}{r^{2}}\left[\frac{1}{\sin\theta}\frac{\partial}{\partial \theta}\left(\sin\theta\frac{\partial\psi}{\partial \theta}\right)+\frac{1}{\sin^{2}\theta}\frac{\partial^{2}\psi}{\partial\phi^{2}}\right]=0	
      </me>
      or,
      <men xml:id="eqn-assoc_legn1">
        \left[\nabla_{r}^{2}+\frac{1}{r^{2}}\nabla^{2}_{\theta,\phi}\right]\psi(r,\theta,\phi) =0
      </men>
      On solving the potential problems some solution yields to relate the Legendre's Polynomials 
      called associated Legendre's polynomials. Let 
      <men xml:id="eqn-assoc_legn2">
        \psi(r,\theta,\phi)=R(r)Y(\theta,\phi)
      </men>
      be the solution of equation <xref ref="eqn-assoc_legn1"/>. Then 
      <me>
        \nabla_{r}^{2}\left[R(r)Y(\theta,\phi)\right]+\frac{1}{r^{2}}\nabla^{2}_{\theta,\phi}\left[R(r)Y(\theta,\phi)\right]=0 
      </me>
      or,
      <me>
        r^{2}\nabla_{r}^{2}\left[R(r)Y(\theta,\phi)\right]=-\nabla^{2}_{\theta,\phi}\left[R(r)Y(\theta,\phi)\right]
      </me>
      Dividing by <m>R(r)Y(\theta,\phi)</m> on both sides, we get -
      <men xml:id="eqn-assoc_legn3">
        \frac{r^{2}}{R}\nabla_{r}^{2}R(r)=-\frac{1}{Y}\nabla^{2}_{\theta,\phi}Y(\theta,\phi) =\lambda \quad \text{(say)}
      </men>
      In equation <xref ref="eqn-assoc_legn3"/> Left Hand Side (LHS) is a function of <m>r</m> 
      only and Right Hand Side (RHS) is a function of <m>(\theta,\phi)</m> only hence 
      such an equation must be equal to some constant, say <m>\lambda </m>. 
      <men xml:id="eqn-assoc_legn4">
        \nabla^{2}_{\theta,\phi}Y(\theta,\phi)+\lambda Y(\theta,\phi) =0
      </men>
      Assume 
      <men xml:id="eqn-assoc_legn5">
       Y(\theta,\phi) = \Theta(\theta)\Phi(\phi) 
      </men>
      be the solution of equation <xref ref="eqn-assoc_legn4"/>, then
      <me>
        \nabla^{2}_{\theta,\phi}\Theta(\theta)\Phi(\phi)+\lambda \Theta(\theta)\Phi(\phi) =0
      </me>
      or,
      <me>
        \left[\frac{1}{\sin\theta}\frac{\partial}{\partial \theta}\left(\sin\theta\frac{\partial}{\partial \theta}\right)+\frac{1}{\sin^{2}\theta}\frac{\partial^{2}}{\partial \phi^{2}}\right]\Theta(\theta)\Phi(\phi)+\lambda \Theta(\theta)\Phi(\phi)=0
      </me>
      or,
      <me>
        \left[\nabla^{2}_{\theta}+\lambda\right]\Theta\cdot\Phi =-\frac{1}{\sin^{2}\theta}\nabla^{2}_{\phi}(\Theta\cdot\Phi)
      </me>
      or,
      <me>
        \sin^{2}\theta\left[\nabla^{2}_{\theta}+\lambda\right]\Theta\cdot\Phi=-\nabla^{2}_{\phi}(\Theta\cdot\Phi)
      </me>
      or,
      <men xml:id="eqn-assoc_legn6">
        \sin^{2}\theta\frac{\nabla^{2}_{\theta}\Theta}{\Theta}+\sin^{2}\theta\lambda=-\frac{\nabla^{2}_{\phi}\Phi}{\Phi}=m^{2}\quad\text{(say)}
      </men>
    </p>
    <p>
      LHS is a function of <m>\theta</m> only and RHS is a function of <m>\phi</m> only 
      which is possible only if they are equal to some constant.  From equation 
      <xref ref="eqn-assoc_legn6"/>,  we have 
      <me>
          \frac{\nabla^{2}_{\phi}\Phi}{\Phi}=-m^{2}
      </me>
      or,
      <men xml:id="eqn-assoc_legn7">
      \frac{\partial^{2}\Phi}{\partial\phi^{2}}+m^{2}\Phi =0
      </men>
    [Azimuthal equation]
       <men xml:id="eqn-assoc_legn8">
      \therefore  \quad \Phi=c_{1}e^{im\phi}+c_{2}e^{-im\phi}=A\cos m\phi+B\sin m\phi
      </men>
      From equation <xref ref="eqn-assoc_legn6"/>
      <me>
        \sin^{2}\theta\frac{\nabla^{2}_{\theta}\Theta}{\Theta}+\lambda\sin^{2}\theta=m^{2} 
      </me>
      or,
      <me>
        \nabla^{2}_{\theta}\Theta+\left(\lambda-\frac{m^{2}}{\sin^{2}\theta}\right)=0
      </me>
      or,
      <men xml:id="eqn-assoc_legn9">
        \frac{1}{\sin\theta}\frac{\partial}{\partial \theta}\left(\sin\theta\frac{\partial\Theta}{\partial \theta}\right)+\left(\lambda-\frac{m^{2}}{\sin^{2}\theta}\right)\Theta =0 
      </men>
      [Theta equation]
      </p>
      <p>
        To solve equation <xref ref="eqn-assoc_legn9"/>, introduce a new variable
        <m>x=\cos\theta</m>
        so that <m>\frac{\,dx}{\,d\theta}=-\sin\theta</m>  and <m>\sin^{2}\theta =1-x^{2}</m>.	
        Therefore, from equation <xref ref="eqn-assoc_legn9"/>, we have 
        <me>
          -\frac{\,d\theta}{\,dx}\cdot\frac{\,d}{\,d\theta}\left(-\frac{\,dx}{\,d\theta}\frac{\,d\Theta}{\,d\theta}\right)+\left(\lambda-\frac{m^{2}}{1-x^{2}}\right)\Theta =0
        </me>
        or,
        <me>
          \frac{\,d}{\,dx}\left(\frac{\,dx}{\,d\theta}\cdot\frac{\,d\Theta}{\,dx}\cdot\frac{\,dx}{\,d\theta}\right)+\left(\lambda-\frac{m^{2}}{1-x^{2}}\right)\Theta =0 
        </me>
        or,
        <me>
          \frac{\,d}{\,dx}\left(\sin^{2}\theta\frac{\,d\Theta}{\,dx}\right)+\left(\lambda-\frac{m^{2}}{1-x^{2}}\right)\Theta =0
        </me>
        or,
        <me>
          \frac{\,d}{\,dx}\left[(1-x^{2})\frac{\,d\Theta}{\,dx}\right]+\left(\lambda-\frac{m^{2}}{1-x^{2}}\right)\Theta =0
        </me>
        <men xml:id="eqn-assoc_legn10">
          (1-x^{2})\frac{d^{2}\Theta}{dx^{2}}-2x\frac{d\Theta}{dx}+\left(\lambda-\frac{m^{2}}{1-x^{2}}\right)\Theta =0
        </men>
        Equation <xref ref="eqn-assoc_legn10"/> is known as associated Legendre's 
        differential equation. If <m>m=0</m>, equation <xref ref="eqn-assoc_legn10"/> becomes 
        Legendre's differential equation.
        <men xml:id="eqn-assoc_legn11">
          (1-x^{2})\frac{d^{2}\Theta}{dx^{2}}-2x\frac{d\Theta}{dx}+\lambda\Theta =0	
        </men>
        If <m>\Theta=y</m> and <m>\lambda=n(n+1) </m> then equation <xref ref="eqn-assoc_legn11"/> 
        is Legendre's differential equation in the cartesian system. From equation 
        <xref ref="eqn-assoc_legn3"/>, we get -
        <me>
          \nabla^{2}_{r}R(r)=\frac{\lambda}{r^{2}}R(r) 
        </me>
        or,
        <me>
      \frac{1}{r^{2}}\frac{d}{dr}\left(r^{2}\frac{dR}{dr}\right)-\frac{\lambda}{r^{2}}R(r)=0
        </me>
        or,
        <men xml:id="eqn-assoc_legn12">
          r^{2}\frac{d^{2}R}{dr^{2}}+2r\frac{dR}{dr}-\lambda R=0
        </men>
        [Radial Equation].
        </p>
</subsubsection>
</subsection>


  </section>

